## Objective: Drive Growth {#objective:-drive-growth}

The retail banking and payments industries are being reshaped by fintech disruptors, open banking, and digital-first customer expectations. Banks must modernize payment systems for real-time transactions, leverage AI for hyper-personalized services, and unify fragmented customer data while ensuring compliance. Enhanced mobile experiences, gamification, and secure data collaboration are critical to driving customer engagement, satisfaction, and retention in an increasingly competitive landscape.

#### Why Change

Retail banks and payment companies face significant technology challenges as they strive to meet evolving customer expectations for real-time, personalized, and seamless experiences. Legacy systems often hinder their ability to modernize payment infrastructures, unify fragmented customer data, and deliver hyper-personalized services. The rapid growth of digital wallets, cryptocurrency, and open banking further intensifies the need for scalable, secure, and compliant platforms. Additionally, balancing innovation with strict regulatory requirements and data privacy standards creates complexity, while ensuring interoperability across ecosystems remains critical for success. Institutions must invest in advanced analytics, AI, and data collaboration tools to stay competitive in this dynamic landscape.

#### Why Now

The urgency for retail banks and payment companies to drive data transformation is fueled by intensifying competition from fintech disruptors, rapidly shifting customer expectations, and technological advancements. Customers now demand real-time, hyper-personalized services and seamless digital experiences, and failing to deliver these can lead to attrition, with many customers switching providers for better offerings. Regulatory pressures and the need to ensure data security and privacy further underscore the necessity of acting now, as delays could result in competitive disadvantage, higher costs, and erosion of customer trust.

#### Business Executives

Chief Marketing Officer (CMO) \- Managing customer engagement and loyalty programs  
Chief Payments Officer (CPO) \- Driving payments strategy and innovation  
Chief Compliance Officer (CCO) \- Ensuring compliance with open banking standards  
Chief Credit Officer (CCO) \- Overseeing credit policies and portfolio management  
Chief Digital Officer (CDxO) \- Leading digital transformation and customer experience

#### Why Databricks

* Delta Sharing: Secure data sharing across partners and third parties  
* Delta Live Tables: Processes transactions in real time with quality expectations  
* Unity Catalog: Provides model transparency with end to end lineage

* Feature Store: Consolidates historical and real-time data serving personalization  
* Generative AI: Reasoning models to better assess customer financial needs  
* MLFlow: Real-time inference model supporting A/B testing

### Strategic Priority: Hyper Personalization & Lead Management {#strategic-priority:-hyper-personalization-&-lead-management}

#### Why change, why now

Retail banking is undergoing significant transformation as traditional banks face fierce competition from neobanks and fintech companies, heightened customer expectations, and historically low satisfaction rates. Customers increasingly demand hyper-personalized experiences and tailored financial services that anticipate their needs, but banks struggle to unify fragmented data across mobile banking, transactions, and service interactions while adhering to strict regulatory compliance and data privacy standards. The rising cost of acquiring new customers, which is 5–6 times higher than retaining existing ones, underscores the critical need to prevent churn and improve customer loyalty. Composable Customer Data Platforms (CDPs) have become essential for consolidating and activating dispersed data, while sophisticated AI models enable deeper insights into customer behavior through transaction analytics and spending patterns.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Prospecting & Campaign Development: Utilize data analytics to identify potential customers and tailor marketing campaigns that resonate with their needs, enhancing engagement and conversion rates.  
* Hyper Personalized Banking: Leverage AI and customer data to deliver tailored banking experiences, improving customer satisfaction and loyalty through personalized insights and recommendations.  
* Cross Sell and Upsell Products: Implement targeted strategies to offer complementary or upgraded products to existing customers, significantly boosting revenue and customer retention.  
* Churn Prediction and Customer Segmentation: Use machine learning models to predict customer churn and segment the customer base effectively, enabling proactive retention efforts and tailored service offerings.

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Personalizing customer experiences.  
Optimizing marketing spend.  
Measuring campaign effectiveness.

#### Key Personas

### Strategic Priority: Cards and Payments Innovation {#strategic-priority:-cards-and-payments-innovation}

#### Why change, why now

The payments industry is undergoing a profound transformation driven by open banking, which facilitates secure data sharing between banks and third-party providers, fostering innovation in real-time payments, account-to-account transfers and digital wallets. Initially launched in the UK/EU in 2017, open banking is now expanding globally, with regulators like the CFPB in the US promoting competitive financial markets by breaking down traditional banking monopolies. This shift is intensifying competition as fintech disruptors challenge traditional banks with seamless digital experiences and innovative products. Emerging technologies like AI and blockchain are accelerating this evolution, with open banking API calls projected to reach 580 billion by 2027\. To stay competitive, banks must modernize their payment systems to meet growing customer expectations for real-time, frictionless, and secure transactions while maintaining compliance in this rapidly evolving landscape.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Partner Offers and Rewards: Leveraging customer transaction data to deliver personalized offers, rewards, and cashback opportunities in collaboration with partner merchants.  
* Transaction Enrichment: Automate the classification of merchants from transaction data to deliver clearer insights into spending patterns.  
* Open Banking Integration: Create seamless data-sharing ecosystems between market participants and banking aggregators through data sharing and API feeds  
* Data Monetization: Generating new revenue streams by leveraging anonymized customer data to deliver insights and create value for third-party partners.

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Increasing cardholder acquisition and retention.  
Reducing processing costs.  
Optimizing payment transaction flows.

#### Key Personas

Head of Consumer Banking  
Head of Payments / Operations  
Head of Innovation & Product Strategy  
Head of Digital Banking

#### Databricks Technical Advantage

Delta Live Tables seamlessly integrates streaming and batch applications, enabling the ingestion, processing, and safeguarding of card transaction data through built-in quality checks and privacy rules. Organizations can create operational dashboards on top of DLT metrics to quickly evaluate the quality and relevance of data from various banking providers and open banking aggregators.

Delta Sharing empowers organizations to exchange information while maintaining full data ownership and reducing friction between different data providers. It streamlines workflows by connecting data directly to business processes, eliminating the need for complex ETL operations.

Unity Catalog offers robust lineage capabilities to track data usage, helping organizations comply with open banking standards like CFPB 1033 by providing transparency into how customer information is processed. Built-in privacy checks automatically detect sensitive PII or PCI data and apply masking rules to ensure compliance and security.

### Strategic Priority: Loans & Personal Investment {#strategic-priority:-loans-&-personal-investment}

#### Why change, why now

Retail banks are intensely focused on improving their Mortgage/Loan Onboarding and Origination processes to gain a competitive edge in today's digital-first financial landscape. By streamlining and automating these processes, banks can significantly reduce operational costs, with potential savings of 30% to 70%, while simultaneously enhancing the customer experience through faster approvals and a seamless digital journey. This modernization allows banks to meet the expectations of tech-savvy consumers, particularly younger generations, by offering the convenience of applying for loans anytime and anywhere. Improved efficiency translates to higher straight-through processing rates and reduced processing times, with some institutions cutting nearly 12 days off their approval timelines. Additionally, digital systems ensure better regulatory compliance, provide valuable data-driven insights for personalized offerings, and enable banks to make more informed lending decisions. Ultimately, these enhancements in Mortgage/Loan Onboarding and Origination processes are crucial for banks to attract and retain customers, drive growth, and maintain competitiveness in an increasingly digital and customer-centric banking environment.

## Objective: Protect the Firm {#objective:-protect-the-firm}

The financial services industry is navigating challenges driven by high interest rates, regulatory pressures, and escalating digital threats. Banks are modernizing operations with AI and advanced analytics to address credit risk, fraud, and compliance inefficiencies while enhancing customer experience through personalized, seamless digital interactions. As operational resilience and security by design become critical, institutions are prioritizing automation and real-time monitoring to reduce costs, improve decision-making, and maintain trust in an evolving landscape.

#### Why Change

Retail banks and payment companies face significant technology challenges as they contend with legacy systems that limit agility, scalability, and innovation. Fragmented data silos hinder real-time insights and efficient decision-making, while rising regulatory pressures demand sophisticated compliance solutions to manage AML, KYC, and fraud detection. The surge in cyber threats and operational risks underscores the need for robust IT systems, cloud adoption, and advanced analytics to enhance resilience and security. Meanwhile, customer expectations for seamless, personalized digital experiences push institutions to invest in AI-driven platforms and modernized infrastructures, balancing transformation costs with the need for stability and trust.

#### Why Now

The urgency for data transformation in retail banking and payments is driven by escalating regulatory pressures and the severe financial and reputational risks of non-compliance. Increasingly complex AML, KYC, and fraud detection standards demand sophisticated, real-time data capabilities to avoid costly fines, such as the recent $3 billion penalty faced by TD Bank. Additionally, the rise in cyber threats and operational vulnerabilities exposes institutions to further regulatory scrutiny and financial losses. Transforming now enables banks to meet compliance demands efficiently, enhance risk management, and ensure operational resilience in an increasingly stringent and high-risk environment.

#### Business Executives

Chief Risk Officer (CRO) \- Overseeing enterprise-wide risk management  
Chief Compliance Officer (CCO) \- Ensuring regulatory adherence and compliance programs  
Chief Legal Officer (CLO) \- Managing legal and regulatory frameworks  
Chief Information Security Officer (CISO) \- Leading cybersecurity strategy

#### Why Databricks

* Data Sharing: Collaboration with market participants for security and compliance  
* Delta Live Tables: Processes telemetry and system logs in real time  
* AI/BI: Provide reporting capabilities to business users using natural language  
* MLFlow: Provide audit capability for model transparency  
* Unity Catalog: Role-based access control safeguarding sensitive data  
* Generative AI: Detect sophisticated threats and automate document processing

### Strategic Priority: Risk Management {#strategic-priority:-risk-management}

#### Why change, why now

The lending landscape is fraught with challenges as high interest rates, rapid digital innovation, and shifting customer expectations disrupt traditional financial operations. Banks are under immense pressure to modernize, but many are hindered by outdated credit-scoring models and limited data sources that fail to accurately assess creditworthiness \- particularly for customers with limited credit history. These shortcomings not only impede financial inclusion but also expose institutions to increased regulatory scrutiny over fair lending practices. Struggling to navigate this complex environment, banks face mounting difficulties in balancing the need for effective debt collection with maintaining customer relationships and adhering to stringent compliance requirements. The adoption of AI-powered underwriting and alternative data sources offers potential solutions, but these technologies bring their own set of integration and implementation hurdles. While modern lending platforms promise faster, more transparent processes and cost reductions, they demand significant investment, expertise, and cultural shifts within institutions already grappling with tight margins and competitive pressures. 

#### Core Use Cases 

* Dynamic pricing: Implement dynamic pricing strategies to adjust loan rates based on real-time risk assessments and customer profiles.  
* Credit decisioning: Utilize advanced analytics and machine learning to streamline credit decisioning processes, improving accuracy in assessing borrower risk.  
* Credit limit increase: Leverage data-driven insights to proactively assess and adjust credit limits based on customer behavior and creditworthiness.  
* Debt collection: Employ predictive analytics to optimize debt collection strategies, identifying the most effective approaches for different customer segments to enhance recovery rates.

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Assessing customer creditworthiness.  
Managing portfolio risk under market fluctuations.  
Ensuring data transparency for regulators.

#### Key Personas

Head of Credit Risk Management  
Head of Consumer / Commercial Banking  
Head of Enterprise Risk Management

#### Databricks Technical Advantage

MLflow simplifies the machine learning lifecycle for credit risk models by offering seamless experimentation tracking, model versioning, and data lineage capabilities. It connects models with their associated data and code, enabling comprehensive audits and expediting model risk management by equipping reviewers with all the necessary context.

Unity Catalog offers role-based access control and dynamic policy masking, ensuring robust protection for sensitive data used in developing and testing risk models. This approach eliminates dependence on outdated or anonymized data, enabling data science teams to build more accurate and effective models. With centralized governance, Unity Catalog ensures regulatory compliance while securely managing all credit \- related data and AI assets.

Delta Live Tables enables real-time processing, allowing banks to monitor card transactions and alternative data sets (e.g. telco data) instantly for accelerated credit risk analysis and loan approvals. Its cloud-native architecture offers scalability to handle large data volumes and complex analytics in real-time. Built-in quality rules provide organizations with a measurable framework to monitor the data quality used in loan decision-making processes.

### Strategic Priority: Regulatory Compliance {#strategic-priority:-regulatory-compliance}

#### Why change, why now

Regulatory compliance has become increasingly complex and costly, with regulatory changes surging by 500% since the 2008 financial crisis, significantly increasing compliance costs. Financial institutions face mounting challenges balancing strict SLAs and poor data quality, as fines are imposed both for incomplete reporting and insufficient controls. These issues are exacerbated by fragmented legacy systems, the need for accuracy across multiple jurisdictions, and reconciling siloed data between risk and accounting systems, all while managing real-time monitoring requirements. AML/KYC controls further strain on resources, as global banks face billions in fines annually, such as TD Bank’s recent $3 billion penalty for failing to detect illicit activities linked to human trafficking and narcotics. With compliance processes costing $1,500 to $3,000 per client review and taking an average of 92 days, institutions employ thousands of staff for KYC tasks, often at the expense of customer satisfaction. Looking ahead, the industry is shifting toward AI-driven RegTech solutions, offering automated reporting, real-time monitoring, and predictive analytics to address these challenges effectively.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Transaction monitoring (AML): Implement real-time transaction monitoring systems to detect suspicious activities and ensure compliance with AML regulations.  
* Screening (KYC): Conduct thorough screening against sanctions lists and politically exposed individuals databases to identify high-risk individuals.  
* IFRS 9 / CECL: Leverage data-driven insights to meet Current Expected Credit Loss (CECL) requirements, ensuring timely recognition of credit losses and improving financial forecasting.  
* SR11 / Model Risk Management: Develop strong model risk management frameworks to consistently validate and review all models utilized by the bank, ensuring their accuracy and reliability while minimizing the risk of errors.  
* CSRD / ESG: Comply with the Corporate Sustainability Reporting Directive (CSRD) and enhance environmental, social, and governance (ESG) reporting practices, improving transparency and accountability.

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Managing data for regulatory audits and reporting.  
Adhering to constantly evolving regulations.  
Reducing compliance reporting timelines.

#### Key Personas

#### What is preventing firms from modernizing?

Banking institutions are stuck in a legacy paradigm that hampers modernization to cloud infrastructure primarily due to concerns around regulatory compliance. The middle office, tasked with ensuring adherence to complex regulations, relies on outdated, siloed systems that are difficult to integrate with modern technologies. This reliance fosters a risk-averse culture, where stability is prioritized over innovation, leading to fears that transitioning to the cloud could invite regulatory scrutiny or operational risks. Additionally, a shortage of skilled personnel who can navigate legacy systems (e.g. SAS, SSIS, Netazza, Oracle, SQL Server), legacy processes, regulatory requirements and new cloud technologies further complicates efforts to modernize. As a result, financial institutions find themselves trapped in a cycle that stifles innovation and hinders the adoption of more efficient solutions like generative AI.

#### How do we win over the Technology Stack?

To modernize regulatory compliance workflows in banking, institutions should prioritize addressing the application layer of their existing systems. This layer serves as the primary interface for compliance professionals, directly impacting their efficiency and effectiveness. By adopting intuitive, user-friendly applications that leverage generative AI for tasks such as document processing and decision-making, banks can significantly enhance workflow efficiency. Once trust is established through improved application performance, organizations can then focus on modernizing the underlying backend infrastructure and their associated data pipelines.

This data & AI Modernization approach requires three primary considerations:

* **Data layer:** The data repositories often sit in legacy DWs such as Oracle, Netezza, Teradata, and/or Hadoop that run large scale datasets and ETL jobs. Work with Bank CTO/CDOs and Risk/Regulatory Business Owners (who often have final decision rights) to assess potential to migrate the data repository.  
* **Business logic:** Risk or regulatory model development is often done on SAS through customer business logic entangled with proprietary solutions. These models are implemented for the production processes.  Full SAS takeout is most challenging given the entrenched user base and legacy tech debt, and likely the last step in your modernization journey.  
* **End application:** Serves models and performs the regulatory computations, analytics, and reconciliation, which tends to be done through a home grown stack and custom made application interfaces. Regardless of where and how models (business logic) are developed, Databricks can provide the production orchestration for the risk and regulatory computations.  Work with your Tech Champion alongside the Risk team and their associated technologist to show our Databricks Technical Advantage. This can be an entry point for Databricks to then win the larger migrations from legacy DWs that host the risk and regulatory data

#### Why change, why now

The recent CrowdStrike outage, which resulted in direct losses for the banking sector and impacted major institutions like Wells Fargo, TD Bank, and Bank of America, underscores the critical importance of operational resilience in banking. This incident highlights the systemic risks posed by proprietary vendor dependencies and the need for robust ITSM processes, proactive monitoring, and automated incident response to protect core banking infrastructure, especially during high-volume periods like Black Friday. At the same time, retail banks face an unprecedented surge in cyber threats, with attacks rising 30% in Q2 2024\. As banks secure digital infrastructures and defend against sophisticated threats like ransomware and advanced persistent threats (APTs), regulators are emphasizing “security by design,” open-source adoption for code and data portability, and improved cloud transparency. To address these challenges, institutions are investing in modern fusion centers that aggregate data from diverse sources, leverage advanced analytics for multi-channel threat detection while enabling faster incident response through unified visibility \- ensuring resilience against both operational failures and cyber threats.

* Infrastructure monitoring: Employ continuous monitoring of IT infrastructure to detect anomalies and potential security breaches in real time, ensuring prompt action can be taken to mitigate risks.

### Strategic Priority: Fraud Prevention {#strategic-priority:-fraud-prevention}

#### Why change, why now

Banks are grappling with an increasingly complex fraud landscape where every $1 lost to fraud now costs financial institutions $4.36 in related expenses such as legal fees and recovery, marking a 16.2% increase since 2020\. The challenge is compounded by sophisticated AI-powered threats with digital forgeries now accounting for 57% of all document fraud \- a staggering 1,600% surge since 2021\. To combat these evolving threats, banks must invest in AI-driven fraud prevention platforms that leverage predictive analytics, behavioral patterns, and geospatial analysis to detect anomalous transactions in real-time, though this technological transformation comes at a challenging time when many institutions are prioritizing cost management. If legacy systems remain the backbone of banking operations / payments, the key to success lies in the bank’s abilities to maintain operational stability while progressively implementing AI-driven fraud detection capabilities, ensuring that customer service and payment processing remain uninterrupted throughout the transformation.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Card transaction fraud prevention: Implement advanced analytics and machine learning to monitor card transactions in real-time, identifying suspicious activities  
* Application Fraud: Utilize robust verification processes and AI-driven document analysis to identify forged documents during the application process.  
* Identity Theft: Leverage graph analytics to uncover hidden relationships and patterns in identity data, enabling banks to detect and prevent identity theft by recognizing suspicious behaviors, from transaction monitoring to identifying entities in the dark web

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Detecting fraud in real time across multiple channels.  
Minimizing false positives that frustrate customers.

## Objective: Operate Efficiently {#objective:-operate-efficiently}

Banks and financial institutions are embracing AI and automation to drive cost efficiency and streamline operations. From automating KYC compliance processes, which can cost thousands per client and take months to complete, to replacing error-prone manual forecasting with predictive analytics, these technologies are reducing operational costs while enhancing accuracy and speed. By leveraging unified data platforms and AI-powered solutions, organizations can transform their processes to be more agile, proactive, and customer-focused, ensuring long-term competitiveness in a volatile market.

#### Why Change

Retail banks and payment companies face significant operational inefficiencies in areas like treasury and middle-office operations, driven by outdated systems, manual processes, and fragmented data. These challenges slow critical functions such as liquidity management, compliance, and fraud detection, increasing costs and limiting agility. Treasury teams often rely on static spreadsheets, which lack the accuracy and scalability needed for dynamic decision-making in volatile markets. To stay competitive, organizations must adopt AI-driven automation and unified data platforms to streamline workflows, enhance middle-office efficiency, and enable proactive, data-driven decisions at scale.

#### Why Now

Banks and payment companies must act now to transform their operations due to mounting pressures from economic volatility, increasing regulatory demands, and rising customer expectations for seamless, real-time services. Inefficient processes and legacy systems not only inflate costs but also hinder agility, making it difficult to respond quickly to market changes or competitive threats. Moreover, the growing prevalence of digital-native competitors highlights the operational inefficiencies of traditional banks, putting their market share and profitability at risk. By embracing data-driven transformation, organizations can reduce costs, enhance decision-making, and position themselves as future-ready in a rapidly evolving financial landscape. Delaying this shift risks falling further behind, both in efficiency and customer trust.

### Strategic Priority: CFO & Treasury {#strategic-priority:-cfo-&-treasury}

#### Why change, why now

Retail banks prioritize improving their Financial Reporting, Cash Flow, and Revenue Projections to enhance and streamline the delivery of actionable data to C-suite executives and finance practitioners. Accurate financial reporting and forecasting provide clear visibility into future cash availability, enabling better decision-making regarding operations, investments, and growth opportunities. By reporting more accurate numbers to both the street and internal C-suite leadership, banks can meet regulatory requirements, provide transparency to stakeholders, and build trust. CFOs and finance teams gain access to near-real-time, accurate data, enabling faster and more informed decision-making. This agility allows organizations to respond swiftly to market changes and capitalize on opportunities. Precise projections serve as a roadmap for future financial performance, supporting strategic initiatives and informing decisions about expansions or new product offerings. Robust financial reporting and forecasting also aid in identifying and mitigating financial risks, managing liquidity more effectively, responding quickly to market changes, and ultimately drive sustainable growth in an increasingly complex financial landscape.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Financial Projections & Reporting: Create accurate financial projections and reports that help banks forecast future performance, manage budgets, and support strategic decision-making.  
* Operational Dashboarding: Develop interactive operational dashboards that consolidate key performance indicators (KPIs) and metrics, enabling real-time monitoring of financial and operational performance  
* Performance reporting and analysis: P\&L statements and KPI dashboards  
* Expense allocations and cost management

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Generating accurate financial forecasts.  
Reducing manual processes in reporting.  
Identifying cost-saving opportunities.

#### Key Personas

Head of Financial Planning and Analysis  
Head of Treasury Operations  
Head of Risk and Controls Compliance

#### Databricks Technical Advantage

Unified lakehouse platform is the only architecture that can help organizations consolidate financial data from multiple sources (through lakehouse federation), eliminating silos to deliver accurate, real-time insights. This unified approach enables improved forecasting and more informed decision-making, ensuring financial institutions can respond dynamically to evolving market conditions.

MLflow streamlines the machine learning lifecycle for cash flow prediction and forecasting models by providing effortless experimentation tracking, model versioning, and data lineage capabilities. By linking models to their underlying data and code, it facilitates thorough audits, addressing the critical materiality of financial models (oftentimes Tier-1) with precision and transparency.

Databricks SQL and AI/BI Genie further democratize data access and analysis. With a user-friendly SQL interface, seamless BI tool integration, and natural language query functionality, these features make analytics accessible to non-technical users.

| DBSQL | Treasury functions are usually not technology savvy and require systems that are easy to use, performant, and visually compelling, making DBSQL and lakeview key components for FP\&A |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DATA ENGINEERING** | Legacy systems are connected through Lakehouse federation and financial records consolidated in gold tables with high quality expectations enforced through Delta Live Tables. |
| **DS/ML** | Forecasting models are considered high materiality models because of the financial impact these have on the banks’ P\&L. MLFlow brings the necessary transparency for audit functions.     |
| **GOVERNANCE** | Unity catalog ensures full auditability of forecasting models and the impact these have on downstream dashboards (lineage). Automated documentation and data quality monitoring are critical for finance teams to run reliable analysis on data they know are correct. |
| **DATA SHARING** | Delta sharing enables collaboration between treasury function and group and can be used to harmonize on premises legacy systems to a modern data platform. |
| **GENERATIVE AI** | Although generative AI might not be relevant as an end use case, the use of generative AI for text to sql , genie and automated table documentation brings easy access to non technology users. |

### Strategic Priority: Back/Middle Office Automation {#strategic-priority:-back/middle-office-automation}

#### Why change, why now

Operational efficiency remains a top priority for retail banks as they seek to automate labor-intensive middle-office and back-office operations effectively. Functions such as customer onboarding, regulatory compliance, and document management often rely on manual processes that are time-consuming, prone to error, and create significant operational strain. For example, a survey indicated that 60% of institutions identified settlement failures linked to middle-office inadequacies, while outdated back-office systems have caused severe consequences \- such as a $900 million mistaken transfer at Citibank, with $500 million unrecoverable due to an antiquated user interface that hadn’t been updated since 2001\. Manual processes like extensive document verification during onboarding can take days to complete, and financial institutions continue to struggle with incompatible payment files, time-intensive manual data entry, and spreadsheet-based reporting. By adopting technologies such as robotic process automation (RPA) and intelligent document processing (IDP), banks can streamline these processes, reducing inefficiencies, operational costs, and risks associated with human error. Furthermore, automation enhances scalability, enables real-time data access for decision-making, and allows institutions to reallocate resources toward higher-value activities that drive innovation and growth, strengthening operational resilience.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Intelligent Document Processing: Implement automated document analysis tools to efficiently extract and verify information from customer documents, streamlining processes and reducing manual errors.  
* Customer onboarding (AML / KYC): Streamline the KYC process, automating identity verification and compliance checks to accelerate customer onboarding and enhance regulatory adherence.  
* Workforce Analytics: Leverage data analytics to optimize employee onboarding processes and improving training programs, ultimately enhancing workforce productivity and engagement.

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Reducing operational overheads.  
Automating repetitive manual workflows.  
Ensuring scalability of operations.

#### Key Personas

Head of Operations Transformation  
Head of Business Process Management  
Head of Enterprise Risk Management

#### Databricks Technical Advantage

The transformative power of Generative AI lies in its ability to reason over data. Tasks like customer onboarding and KYC, traditionally labor-intensive, can be streamlined (if not fully automated) through the use of AI agents. Generative AI can streamline data ingestion by intelligently processing unstructured data and complex documents,  contracts, and policies. 

The Databricks architecture, powered by Unity Catalog governance, Delta Sharing, and Lakehouse federation, ensures seamless data interoperability across diverse systems—whether on-premises or cloud-based, proprietary or open source. This design enables effortless collaboration while reducing the reliance on labor-intensive middle-office operations to translate data between systems.

All processes, pipelines, and model inferences are logged into system tables, which can be made accessible to compliance and audit teams. These teams can then monitor the quality of middle-office operations and ensure that automated processes align with regulatory compliance guidelines through intuitive AI/BI dashboards and natural language queries.

| DBSQL | Operation metrics are mapped to business processes in a central platform that can monitor efficiency ratio through dashboard, visualizations and text to sql capabilities (AI/BI).  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DATA ENGINEERING** | AI agents are built to connect to back office systems through APIs in an overarching automation strategy.  Agents must be governed centrally with enhanced levels of scrutiny for decision making processes. |
| **DS/ML** | ML algorithms can identify unusual patterns in data, such as errors in financial transactions or irregular activities, enabling automated intervention before issues escalate. These models feed business processes and therefore must be governed through MLFlow \+ UC with the highest scrutiny. |
| **GOVERNANCE** | Any system input / output of any agent (being API requests or models or RAG) must be logged into system tables to ensure business processes are properly followed through with full transparency.  |
| **DATA SHARING** | Delta Sharing facilitates data portability and interoperability across multiple systems and clouds, ensuring programmatic access (vs. manual) to core business processes. |
| **GENERATIVE AI** | Multiple generative AI models can be combined together through an AI gateway and enriched with tools (agents) that must be properly designed and constantly re-evaluated by business users through a simple interface and audit log. |

### Strategic Priority: Call center and Channel Optimization {#strategic-priority:-call-center-and-channel-optimization}

#### Why change, why now

Banks are transforming their call centers and physical branches to balance operational efficiency with exceptional customer experience in response to shifting market trends. While 82% of customers prefer digital channels for routine tasks, 45% still value face-to-face interactions for complex financial decisions, prompting banks to reimagine branches as hybrid spaces that blend digital efficiency with human expertise. Similarly, call centers are evolving into strategic touchpoints, using AI to optimize Interactive Voice Response (IVR) systems and streamline complaint resolution. Generative AI technologies enhance this transformation by automating routine inquiries and offering context-aware support, ensuring efficiency gains without compromising customer satisfaction. This dual focus on automation and experience positions banks to reduce costs, improve service quality, and meet the demands of a rapidly evolving financial landscape.

#### Core Use Cases 

* Branch network optimization: Identify underperforming branches and develop strategies for closures or consolidations, ensuring an efficient and cost-effective branch network.  
* Complaint management: Implement automated systems to categorize and prioritize customer complaints, allowing banks to streamline resolution processes and reduce operational costs associated with customer service.  
* Intelligent IVR / Chatbots: Deploy AI-driven intelligent IVR and chatbots that can handle routine inquiries and seamlessly re-route complex issues to human agents.

#### Key Objectives / KPIs

Reducing operational overheads whilst maintaining customer satisfaction.  
Automating repetitive manual workflows.  
Ensuring scalability of operations.

#### Key Personas

Head of Operations Transformation  
Head of Customer Service Operations  
Head of Consumer Banking  
Head of Digital Banking

#### Databricks Technical Advantage

Databricks equips customer advocacy teams with advanced AI/BI tools to monitor satisfaction metrics and transform insights using natural language. These capabilities enable teams to quickly understand customer feedback and improve decision-making processes.

To manage large volumes of unstructured data (call details, IVR, CCTV), banks can leverage OCR libraries and Generative AI models within ETL processes, preparing data for more detailed analysis. This enables deeper insights into customer interactions and streamlines the analysis of various data types. AI Gateway centralizes access to both open-source and proprietary models, facilitating tasks such as complaint classification.

Digitized documents are securely managed through Unity Catalog, ensuring compliance with GDPR and CCPA regulations. This comprehensive approach empowers call center agents to move beyond basic inquiries, offering guided solutions that enhance the overall customer experience.

| DBSQL | AI/BI and Lakeflow dashboard empower customer advocacy teams to monitor satisfaction metrics and transform data insights into targeted actions, enabling consistent and enhanced customer experiences across all interaction channels. |
| :---- | :---- |
| **DATA ENGINEERING** | Though multi-modal models can be used for unstructured data, OCR libraries are incorporated into ETL processes prior to running LLM analysis given the scale of information at hand. |
| **DS/ML** | AI Gateway provides organizations with a centralized, secured and governed access to open source or proprietary models that are used for complaint classification or CCTV review, leveraging the right model for the right task in a cohesive genAI strategy. |
| **GOVERNANCE** | Digitized customer documents are centrally managed through Volumes, which applies enterprise-grade governance and security protocols \- matching the stringent standards used for structured data \- while maintaining full compliance with GDPR, CCPA, and other data privacy regulations. |
| **DATA SHARING** | Consolidating all data from multiple systems, being local branches (e.g. CCTV records) to external 3rd party systems (IVR). Delta Sharing creates a protocol that facilitates integration of multiple systems through a data mesh type of architecture. |
| **GENERATIVE AI** | Compound AI systems are decomposing complex customer inquiries into manageable subtasks, enabling call centers agents to progress beyond basic chatbot interactions to deliver systematic, guided problem resolution |
